📌 PHASE 3 – DATABASE DESIGN

Before creating tables, every company asks:

"What data do we need to store?"

Let's think like database designers.

🏢 Imagine this scenario

Our client gives us one job posting.

Job ID : 101
Job Title : Data Analyst
Salary : ₹12 LPA
Location : Hyderabad
Skills : SQL, Python, Excel

Now here's my question.

❓Should we store everything in ONE table?

Example:

Job ID	Job Title	Salary	Skill1	Skill2	Skill3
101	Data Analyst	12 LPA	SQL	Python	Excel

Looks okay?

❌ Actually, NO.

Why?

Imagine another job.

Job ID	Job Title	Salary	Skill1	Skill2	Skill3
102	Data Scientist	18 LPA	Python	SQL	Machine Learning

Now imagine a company asks for 10 skills.

Where will you store them?

Skill4
Skill5
Skill6
Skill7
...
Skill10

😵 The table becomes huge.

🤔 Another problem

Suppose SQL appears in 1000 jobs.

You'll write

SQL
SQL
SQL
SQL
SQL
SQL

1000 times.

That's called Data Redundancy.

It wastes storage and makes updates harder.

💡 Solution?

Database designers split the data into multiple tables.

This is called Normalization.

👉 Normalization means:

Organizing data into separate tables to reduce duplicate data and improve efficiency.

Remember this definition. Interviewers love asking it.

📌 So why do we need 3 tables?
🟦 Table 1: job_postings_fact

This stores job information only.

Example:

Job ID	Title	Salary	Location
101	Data Analyst	12 LPA	Hyderabad
102	Data Scientist	18 LPA	Bangalore

Notice...

No skills here.

Only job details.

🟩 Table 2: skills_dim

This stores each skill only once.

Skill ID	Skill
1	SQL
2	Python
3	Excel
4	Power BI

Now SQL is stored only one time.

That's efficient.

🟨 Table 3: skills_job_dim

This is the bridge between jobs and skills.

Job ID	Skill ID
101	1
101	2
101	3
102	2
102	1

Let's understand it.

Job 101 requires:

Skill ID 1 → SQL
Skill ID 2 → Python
Skill ID 3 → Excel

Job 102 requires:

Skill ID 2 → Python
Skill ID 1 → SQL

Simple!

🎯 Why can't we directly connect jobs to skills?

Because...

One job can require many skills.

Example:

Data Analyst

↓

SQL
Python
Excel
Power BI
Tableau

At the same time...

One skill like SQL belongs to many jobs.

SQL

↓

Data Analyst
Data Engineer
Data Scientist
Business Analyst
Database Developer

So the relationship is:

One Job
     ↔
Many Skills

AND

One Skill
     ↔
Many Jobs

This is called a Many-to-Many Relationship.

Since relational databases cannot directly store a many-to-many relationship, we create a bridge (junction) table, which is skills_job_dim.

🖼️ Here's the complete picture
             job_postings_fact
             -----------------
             job_id (PK)
             job_title
             salary
             location
                  |
                  |
             job_id (FK)
                  |
          skills_job_dim
          ----------------
          job_id (FK)
          skill_id (FK)
                  |
                  |
             skill_id
                  |
             skills_dim
             ----------
             skill_id (PK)
             skill_name

This is the database design we'll build in MySQL.

